<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Credit Lyonnais to take controlling stake in BfG
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT Lyonnais, the aggressive French state-owned bank, yesterday won
agreement to take 50.1 per cent control of BfG Bank, Germany's sixth largest
private commercial bank, for DM1.42bn (Pounds 570m).
This is the climax of a five-year campaign by Credit Lyonnais to boost its
presence in Germany, the biggest gap in its international branch network.
BfG has 170 branches in western Germany against which Credit Lyonnais has
23.
The French bank will pump an initial DM740m of equity into undercapitalised
BfG. DM540m will be in cash and the remainder as shares in its German
subsidiary, Credit Lyonnais Deutschland.
This will give Credit Lyonnais an initial 26 per cent stake. It will buy the
24.1 per cent balance to obtain a majority in equal parts from BfG's
existing owners, Aachener und Munchener Beteiligungs (AMB), the insurance
group, and BGAG, the German trades union holding company.
Credit Lyonnais, the latest in a long line of big French investors in
Germany, hoped to improve access to the German market through a partnership
with Commerzbank, Germany's third largest bank, but four years of talks
broke down last autumn.
AGF, the French state-owned insurer, asked Credit Lyonnais to consider
buying BfG early this year to help the insurance group consummate a separate
alliance with AMB.
The German insurer, looking for an exit from what had proved a costly
diversification into banking with formerly loss-making BfG, agreed terms
with AGF. Yesterday's deal completes a rare example of two French
state-owned groups helping each other in the German market.
BfG, which yesterday welcomed the deal, is restructuring. Its staff has been
cut from 7,000 to 5,200, allowing it to make a DM120m operating profit last
year, against a DM390m loss a year earlier.
Mr Alexis Wolkenstein, managing director of Credit Lyonnais Europe, said BfG
should be profitable this year, but this depended on provisions on BfG's
DM3.5bn of sovereign loans.
It set aside 50 per cent provisions for bad sovereign debt at the end of
last year, and this would rise to more than 70 per cent in the current year,
said Mr Wolkenstein.
</TEXT>
