<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Heseltine placates industry with offer of partnership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday held out an
olive branch to UK industry by offering it a partnership with government.
Addressing the annual conference of the Confederation of British Industry at
Harrogate, Mr Heseltine said: 'Such a partnership is essential if we are to
succeed in the world marketplace.' Anything else would be 'an abdication of
national self-interest'.
Mr Heseltine refused to disclose details of financial assistance to industry
ahead of Mr Norman Lamont's Autumn Statement tomorrow. He hinted, however,
that the chancellor would be announcing help for exporters through increased
export credits.
He also announced that Lord Sainsbury, retired chairman of J. Sainsbury, the
supermarket group, would act as his adviser on deregulation and the fight
against red tape. CBI delegates, who had been bitterly critical of the
government earlier in the conference, seemed broadly satisfied with the
speech.
Sir Michael Angus, CBI president, said: 'I think the open season on
government should be closed.' Mr Howard Davies, CBI director general, said:
'What we heard today was what we hoped to hear. He clarified what he saw as
his role.'
Earlier, Mr Heseltine had heard a barrage of criticism of government from
conference speakers.
Mr Neil Ashley of Amey Holdings, the construction group, said: 'Any
government that spends Pounds 70bn a year on social and unemployment
spending and only Pounds 2bn on roads is not over-endowed with vision'.
Mr Norman Sussmann of the British Clothing Industry Association asked: 'Is
the U-turn on the miners the first sign that the government is beginning to
recognise the importance of manufacturing industry?'
Mr Heseltine said: 'I have never subscribed to the view that manufacturing
industry doesn't matter. We built this nation's economy on it. Our principal
competitors thrive on it.' He added: 'We need to build the impact of
industry across Whitehall. This is a cultural change.'
Mr Heseltine also urged delegates not to grant high wages. 'Wage settlements
continue at a level that cannot be afforded,' he said. 'The message that the
CBI has a central role in getting a grip on wages, including in the board
room, cannot be overstated.'
Sir Bob Reid, chairman of British Rail, welcomed the pledge to ensure that
industry's needs were appreciated in Whitehall. But the real proof of the
government's new approach would come with the Autumn Statement, which had to
preserve capital spending programmes and permit flexibility in public
financing.
Conference reports, Page 11
How to help industry, Page 20
</TEXT>
