FT  11 NOV 92 / Observer: Survival test
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The fact that Sir Peter Abeles, the buccaneering Australian tycoon who
founded TNT, missed the group's annual meeting should not come as a total
surprise. He lives a highly pressured existence.
Sir Peter is expected to recover in about a week, but the episode bears out
suggestions that he exhausted himself by working much too hard on trying to
solve TNT's intractable problems over the past two years.
More surprising was the announcement that Abeles is not going to spend his
retirement, after all, helping to sort out the problems of Ansett, the
airline jointly-owned by TNT and Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation. TNT says
that Sir Peter had decided that Ansett's return to modest operating profits
in the latest quarter meant the airline could safely be left in the hands of
Ken Cowley, Murdoch's top man in Australia, who is joint chairman. A more
likely explanation is that Ansett's owners may be nervous about Sir Peter's
swashbuckling approach to the airline's problems.
