<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Italian novelist Primo Levi was a member of that relatively small band of
people who were sent to Auschwitz by the Nazis and survived to bear witness
to the world. The terrible thing is that, 40 years after the event, he was
still so appalled by what he had seen and by the belief that it could, all
too easily, happen again that he killed himself. Primo Levi: The Memory Of
The Offence (8.10 BBC2) tells the story of his life using his own prose and
poetry and the memories of his friends.
Dispatches (9.00 C4) provides another unflattering story about the Germans,
this time during the cold war. It seems that East Germans wishing to escape
to the West but not wanting to risk the guns of the border guards could pay
Wolfgang Vogel. His fixer role appears to have been accepted in both East
and West Germany, but his deals meant that escapers often lost their houses
or spent considerable periods in prison.
Fatal Attraction (9.00 ITV) is one of those movies which achieved huge
success largely via a campaign of vilification. Feminists took exception to
the portrayal of a woman, during an affair, as predatory and hysterical.
</TEXT>
