<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Councils to suffer squeeze on
spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's limits on local authority spending for next year will be
even more tightly drawn than the 'capping' regime operating this year.
The criteria for limiting council budgets will be set out in a statement by
Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, towards the end of the month,
and will intensify the squeeze on local spending, as part of the
government's determination to keep council tax bills from rising too
steeply.
For spending in 1992-93, the regime put in place by the Department of the
Environment is based on both what had been spent in 1991-92 and the standard
spending assessment (SSA) - what the government thought the councils should
be spending in 1992-93.
That system will remain, but the percentage increases allowed will be
reduced.
The government's argument is that with a lower inflation rate expected for
1993-94 than for 1992-93, councils have less need to increase spending.
There is also ministerial concern that in the current year, even with the
strictness of the existing capping regime, actual local spending looks
likely to exceed the government limits of Pounds 41.8bn for England by just
over Pounds 1bn.
The transfer of further education spending away from local authorities to a
new funding council will make the capping arrangements particularly
difficult this year.
Councils who were spending less on further education than the government
estimate of what they needed to spend will find their budgets adjusted to
take account of what the government had assumed they should be spending
rather than what they actually spent. This could mean that they have to make
cuts in other services.
Local authorities are already insisting that they will need a government
grant to take account of the impact on their 1993-94 spending of pay deals
for groups such as the police which have already been agreed.
The local authority associations estimate that such pay deals will cost them
Pounds 228m in 1993-94, regardless of the public sector pay squeeze to be
announced tomorrow in the Autumn Statement.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
