<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Renewal offer to MMI clients
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities unable to obtain insurance cover in the wake of the
problems of Municipal Mutual (MMI), the UK's ninth largest insurer, are to
be offered new facilities by Zurich Insurance. The giant Swiss company has
been in negotiations with MMI over the past month, Richard Lapper writes.
Up to 300 local authorities, whose policies come up for renewal between
October and the start of January, could be insured by Zurich. Some 31,000
individual policyholders are also being offered renewals by the Swiss
company.
MMI, which has incurred heavy losses on its liability business, withdrew
from the insurance market in September, leaving a number of local
authorities temporarily without insurance. MMI insured nine out of 10 local
councils but other UK companies have been reluctant to offer cover.
However, Mr Brian Wright, group chief executive, said talks with Zurich were
'going well'. MMI hopes to be able to transfer most of its business to the
Swiss company, which would also employ a large number of the 2,000 staff.
Zurich is understood to be reluctant to assume any liabilities arising on
policies already underwritten by MMI.
Mr Dennis White, chief executive of Zurich Insurance UK, said: 'There are
some complex issues involved which will yet need to be resolved but we are
making genuine progress.'
</TEXT>
