<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Pits would require 'months' to restart
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 10 PITS earmarked for closure or already closed by British Coal would
need up to nine months of work before they could operate fully, Mr Doug
Bulmer, president of the British Association of Colliery Management, said
yesterday.
He told the Commons trade and industry committee some of the pits could be
re-opened quickly but in some cases six to nine months would be necessary
before equipment was fully operational. British Coal is undergoing a 90-day
consultation period with unions about the future of the pits.
Mr Bulmer called for the dismissal of Professor Stephen Littlechild, the
electricity regulator.
British Coal's decision to close 31 pits, announced last month, had not been
a surprise because of 'the way in which the power generation market has been
rigged against coal and in favour of gas', he said.
'It came as no surprise to the government or the electricity regulator and
we have provided documentary evidence of that. In our view the regulator
should be dismissed for dereliction of duty. We are being pushed out of the
power generation market, quite irrespective of our ability to get costs down
to compete with imported coal and other fuels.' Mr Bulmer said.
'Gas is to be burned in preference to coal, despite its higher price,
because of the way the electricity supply industry is organised,' he said.
</TEXT>
