<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Changes in partnership legislation proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARTNERSHIPS comprising unlimited liability companies will be required to
file publicly available accounts after January 1995, according to a
consultative document issued by the Department of Trade and Industry
yesterday.
Legislation will be introduced after that date to include partnerships,
limited partnerships and unlimited companies in which the members are
limited companies. This will bring UK law into line with amendments to the
EC's fourth and seventh company law directives.
Mr Neil Hamilton, minister for corporate affairs, who launched the
consultative document, said that the changes would affect very few British
partnerships because most were formed between people rather than limited
companies.
Most companies that form partnerships already include the partnership
accounts with their own annual accounts. Those that do not will have to do
so in future. If all the partner companies are abroad, the partnership may
have to make its accounts available on demand at its main office.
The document says there were 486,834 partnerships registered for value added
tax this year, 3,193 limited partnerships and 4,000 unlimited companies.
The DTI said it wanted to hear about the potential costs of compliance.
Comments on the document should be received by January 22.
</TEXT>
