<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Move to ease fears over coal contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government will try to ease the uncertainty over British Coal's new
long-term coal contracts by stating whether it would be willing to see them
concluded before the results of its energy policy review are known.
The electricity industry is trying to pull together a five-year deal with
British Coal, on which its future depends. But talks are stalled because
several companies are unwilling to commit themselves to a deal while the
review is in progress.
Although British Coal is negotiating with the power generators, these need
to secure long-term supply deals with the distribution companies in England
and Wales before the whole package can be agreed.
The government will make its view known in a Commons written answer from Mr
Tim Eggar, the energy minister, in the next few days. The answer will take
account of the fact that talks on the contracts must progress so that new
terms can be in place by next April when the current ones expire.
But they must leave room to accommodate extra coal deliveries if this is the
effect of the new policy, which will not become known until the new year.
Mr John Baker, chief executive of National Power, estimated yesterday that
the 12 regional electricity companies are equally divided between those
which are ready to sign new contracts, those which are not, and those which
are awaiting guidance.
He said National Power was looking into the possibility of signing long-term
deals with individual companies rather than waiting for an industry-wide
agreement. But it is likely the companies will be wary of committing
themselves if their competitors do not because they may forfeit competitive
advantage.
