<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Ofwat warns on efficiency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WATER COMPANIES which are inefficient will face tighter price controls in
future, the industry regulator Ofwat said yesterday.
Ofwat's consultation paper said it would look favourably on water companies
which controlled costs and had high standards of customer service when it
conducts its periodic review in 1994 - a wide-ranging assessment of the
industry's pricing structure.
Mr Ian Byatt, Ofwat director-general, said yesterday: 'I am concerned about
the rising level of water and sewerage bills.'
The water companies' 10-year modernisation programme to bring water
standards in England and Wales into line with European Community directives
could eventually cost about Pounds 45bn.
Ofwat's paper said the rate of price increases 'must bear some relationship
to the costs incurred but the relationship need not be a mechanical one.
Companies which are shown to be less efficient will be set tighter price
limits.'
The paper added that increases in water charges would allow water companies
to make a 'reasonable' return on capital and that it would not try to 'claw
back retrospectively any savings companies have made above the efficiency
targets initially assumed'.
Mr David Luffnam, finance director of Thames Water, said: 'There are a
number of positive things such as being able to retain efficiency gains for
a good period. But this is just one step towards the periodic review, and
the crunch clearly comes with the next part - the assumptions about what are
acceptable financial ratios.'
Lex, Page 22
