<DOCNO>FT924-8467</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKKCIABMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921111
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / NatWest to close 35 bank branches in West End
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank is to close 35 of its 90 branches in the West End
of London over the next five years and move their back-office work to two
processing centres. The reorganisation may serve as a model for branch
banking nationally.
About 300 of the 2,900 jobs in the West End are likely to be lost. The money
saved will be spent on redesigning remaining branches to allow more
interaction between staff and customers.
National Westminster said yesterday that there would be no compulsory
redundancies. The cuts will form part of national reductions. The bank wants
to lose 10,000 staff over the next two years.
The new design will allow more space for selling products such as
investments, mortgages and foreign currency. There will also be more space
for automatic teller machines in the open-plan branches.
The bank said the West End would be the first of its 22 regions to complete
the reorganisation. It was likely that a smaller proportion of branches
would be closed elsewhere.
The West End has a large number of branches dating from the merger of the
National Provincial and Westminster banks. The bank has about 2,500 branches
across the country, the largest branch network of any clearer.
All clearing banks are trying to reorganise branch networks to cut costs and
sell more products. They are attempting to reduce processing costs by
centralising functions such as cheque clearing.
National Westminster is allocating more staff to act as account managers to
ensure each customer has access to one. It opened a model new branch in
Victoria Street, London, 18 months ago which reverses the traditional
proportion of floorspace, giving customers more space than staff for the
first time.
Standard Chartered Plc will make 77 of its 1,000-strong UK banking staff
redundant by the end of the year. The bank said the redundancies would be
among operational staff in corporate banking.
