<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / Consumer group warns on rail sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE privatisation of British Rail should be abandoned unless some serious
questions about the government's plans can be satisfactorily answered, the
National Consumer Council says in a report today.
The report is an embarrassment to the Department of Transport because the
council is government-funded and Lady Wilcox, who chairs it, is a member of
the prime minister's advisory committee on the Citizen's Charter.
Lady Wilcox said the council's own research showed that many rail passengers
were unhappy with BR, but it was not yet clear that privatisation was the
way to make train services better. 'My council says emphatically that unless
satisfactory answers are forthcoming to the questions they are asking, they
do not believe that privatisation of British Rail will be in consumers' best
interests.'
Among fears voiced by the council's report are:
Reductions in state subsidies could result in fewer trains and higher fares.
It is not clear how standards of frequency and punctuality will be enforced.
Passengers may lose benefits such as season tickets, travel cards, through
ticketing and national timetables.
Blame for service failures will be hard to establish once responsibility for
train operation and track ownership has been divided.
The council adds that train operators will be at a disadvantage to road
transport operators if, as envisaged, they have to pay Railtrack, the body
that will own the track after privatisation, a fee based on the number of
journeys they make. It suggests instead a flat-rate licence fee similar to
the road licence fee.
British Rail Privatisation, National Consumer Council, 20 Grosvenor Gardens,
London SW1W 0DH. Free with A4 SAE.
</TEXT>
