FT  11 NOV 92 / Argentine trade gap wider than predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Domingo Cavallo, Argentina's economy minister, has admitted that this
year's trade deficit is likely to be far larger than he estimated less than
three weeks ago. In a speech to businessmen on Monday, he also warned that
economic integration with Brazil was at risk.
Mr Cavallo said that he now expected a deficit of Dollars 1.2bn-Dollars
1.4bn in 1992, after forecasting last month a deficit of up to Dollars 1bn
(Pounds 645m). Argentina has not seen a trade deficit since 1981 and in 1991
ran a Dollars 3.87bn surplus.
Mr Cavallo had said a deficit was no cause for concern, as it would be
covered by capital inflows or would force an adjustment in the domestic
economy. However, last month he increased industry's protection from foreign
competition by trebling to 10 per cent a tax on nearly all imports, to try
to slow shipments from Brazil, Argentina's partner in the Mercosur trade
pact.
Mr Cavallo warned in his speech that economic instability in Brazil was
making integration impossible.
