<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 92 / UK-French relations sour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DIPLOMATIC row simmered between Britain and France yesterday following a
sharp reply by Mr John Major to President Francois Mitterrand's criticism of
the UK's new timetable for the ratification of the Maastricht treaty.
Answering Mr Mitterrand's attack on the slowness with which the British
government intended to proceed with ratification, Mr Major issued a vigorous
warning that the timing was a matter for the UK, and not for its EC
partners.
The prime minister told MPs he had written to Mr Mitterrand giving his
views.
He added: 'I am quite prepared to state publicly that the passage of the
Maastricht bill is a matter for the British parliament and for the British
government.'
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, also rejected the French criticism
yesterday, at the launch of a government pamphlet which explains the treaty.
'A treaty delayed is better than a treaty destroyed or lost,' Mr Hurd said.
The treaty would in Britain undergo more detailed scrutiny than in any other
EC state. Britain had always made clear to its EC partners that this would
take a long time, he said. It was natural enough that countries which had
already ratified the treaty felt a certain amount of anxiety. But Mr Hurd
said that, in spite of that anxiety, there was a feeling that the treaty
would be ratified.
Mr Major's linking of the French president's remarks on Maastricht with the
need to prevent a trade war, was seen at Westminster as a veiled suggestion
that Mr Mitterrand was trying to use ratification as a diversion from
France's stubborn refusal to make further concessions to the US in the
Uruguay Round of trade talks.
Mr Mitterrand last night reiterated his frustration at the British intention
to delay ratification until at least next May, allegedly until after the
result of the second Danish referendum.
Speaking at a joint press conference with Mr Giuliano Amato, the Italian
prime minister, the French president said: 'Everyone should accept his
responsibilities. We have all signed this treaty. It is now necessary to put
it in place.
'One can well understand that the British government needs a bit of time to
deal with its own problems, but one cannot hinder the process (of
ratification) that is already under way.'
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany is also likely to voice his concern at the
consequences of Britain's delayed timetable when he meets Mr Major at a
bilateral summit at Ditchley Park, near Oxford, today.
A main worry for the German leader is the threat of a delay in talks with
new applicants for European Community membership, strongly backed by Britain
and Germany, and due to begin on January 1.
They include Austria, Finland and Sweden, which have already applied, and
Norway and Switzerland, which are expected to do so. Mr Kohl would like
those talks to go ahead regardless of the delay in ratification, but other
EC members seem likely to block them until ratification is completed, thus
undermining one of the top priorities of the British EC presidency.
However, Mr Kohl, anxious to preserve his good personal relations with the
prime minister, is unlikely to attack Mr Major openly for his decision to
postpone the Maastricht ratification process.
German officials recognise it is a question for each individual member state
to decide.
Mr Kohl will also throw his weight behind any initiative Mr Major is ready
to take to reach a settlement between the EC and the US in the trade talks.
Mr Major also had talks in London yesterday with Mr Ruud Lubbers, the Dutch
prime minister, who made it clear that he too had strong reservations about
the British policy on ratification.
The official British line was that Mr Lubbers had expressed 'no complaints
or recriminations against the British position'. But outside 10 Downing
Street, Mr Lubbers told Dutch television that he did not understand what
Britain was doing and that he was disappointed with its position on the
Maastricht treaty.
