FT  10 NOV 92 / ICI demerger is on course for 1993, confirms chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIR DENYS Henderson, chair-man of Imperial Chemical Industries, yesterday
confirmed that the organisational split of the group's pharmaceuticals,
agrochemicals and specialities businesses into a separate company was on
track. He said the new company would be fully formed as a subsidiary of ICI
by January 1, 1993.
A final decision to go ahead with the demerger of the group into two
separately quoted companies would be made at the February meeting of the ICI
board, said Sir Denys.
The board would look at the financial position of the whole company and
forecasts for the group's performance next year.
Sir Denys, speaking in Taiwan where ICI was opening a Pounds 150m facility,
declined to comment on whether ICI would maintain its full-year dividend.
The board would also consider the state of the stock market to establish
whether it would be possible to issue fresh shares in the bioscience
company, he said.
Analysts believe most of ICI's liabilities would be given to the bioscience
group, freeing the bulk chemicals operations from debt. The bioscience
businesses would then issue shares to clear their debt and raise cash for
possible acquisitions.
Sir Denys warned that the pharmaceutical division's operating profits next
year would be flat. The division generated trading profits of Pounds 538m
last year, equivalent to 52 per cent of ICI's total pre-tax profit on 12 per
cent of group sales. Next year agrochemicals would improve on poor
performance during 1992, he added. 'There's a lot of money looking for
quality stocks,' he said. 'As a company, the bioscience business should be
quite attractive - in fact, that is British under-statement, they should be
very attractive.'
The bioscience company, which had previously been referred to as ICI
Bioscience, would be renamed to create a new identity, said Sir Denys.
Details of the progress of the demerger process will be given on November
18.
Sir Denys denied that advanced corporation tax would prove a stumbling block
to the demerger. ICI did not face an unrelieved ACT problem yet, although at
some stage it would happen because the group generates more than 80 per cent
of its turnover outside the UK.
Risky gamble, Page 4
