<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / The Lex Column: Costain/Hanson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Whatever the outcome of the little spat between Costain and Hanson over
Costain's Australian coal interests, both sides look like losers. Hard on
the heels of losing RHM to Tomkins, Hanson could do without the public
relations headache of another deal turning sour. Given Costain's need to
reduce debt, it is hardly in its interest for the whole thing to be bogged
down in the courts. The difference between the two is that Hanson can better
afford the inconvenience.
That Costain needs to sell its prime asset is underlined by how little the
shares have risen since the original deal was announced. Even when the money
comes in, gearing will be about 50 per cent. If the preference shares are
repaid next year and cash flow remains negative, gearing may well rise to
around 70 per cent, even without further asset writedowns. To add to its
woes, much of Costain's debt is denominated in dollars: it will not benefit
from falling UK rates, but will be hurt by the devaluation of sterling when
its hedging runs out.
Meanwhile the company is stuck with an underperforming US coal operation and
its basic UK contracting and construction business. Costain badly needs an
upturn in the UK construction market to revive its fortunes. The Autumn
Statement notwithstanding, that looks as depressingly far away as ever.
</TEXT>
