FT  10 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Channel 4's art and culture magazine programme Without Walls (9.00) looks
into the origins of the Volkswagen Beetle which it describes as 'Hitler's
baby' and 'a symbol of Nazism'. It seems that Hitler handed his own sketches
for the car to Ferdinand Porsche, who is generally credited as its creator.
Second half of the programme is devoted to the design of sports stadiums.
Kinsey (9.30 BBC1) is another of those law series which is about marriage,
children, drugs, almost anything but the law, really. In the title role
Leigh Lawson has a wonderful time wearing a Clint Eastwood 'duster' coat
while all sorts of women dance attendance upon him: ex-wife, doting
secretary, new (spiffing redhead) partner. However, at the end of the last
episode his daughter arrived at his office after being thrown out of school
and the tables look ready for turning.
Sir John Harvey-Jones begins Troubleshooter 2 by revisiting the firms which
were the subjects of his first series (Morgan Cars, Churchill pottery,
Tri-ang toys and so on). Later in this new series he will be offering his
advice to six more businesses and organisations (9.45 BBC2).
