<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / The CBI at Harrogate: Out of the shadows and back into the
industrial limelight - A new respect for the views of the employers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF YOU listen carefully to the platform party at this year's CBI conference,
you can almost hear the sound of purring. At long last the CBI is being
taken seriously by the government.
Cabinet ministers and civil servants have flocked to address the conference
and seek its opinions. For an organisation which spent much of the 1980s in
the shadows, the result is an unaccustomed glow of self-importance.
The change is not difficult to account for. The government has been giving
greater emphasis to stimulating growth than to combatting inflation. At the
same time, ministers appear to be losing faith in a consumer-led economic
revival. The only alternative is an investment-led recovery, and if the
government cannot afford such investment itself, it is up to the CBI's
membership to come to the rescue.
Whether those members are in the mood to oblige is altogether another
matter. The CBI's own surveys suggest that investment in plant and machinery
next year will fall for the fourth consecutive year.
The first report from its new National Manufacturing Council, produced with
a flourish on the first day of the conference, set a target of doubled
investment per employee by UK industry by the year 2000. From the
government's viewpoint, that may appear to be a somewhat leisurely
programme.
In return, the CBI seeks help from the government in the form of lower rates
of corporation tax and higher capital allowances. It also looks to the City
for easier bank finance and the acceptance of lower dividend payments to
shareholders.
That last point was returned to repeatedly by speakers from the floor
yesterday. The argument is familiar: that in competing nations such as
Germany and Japan, a much larger proportion of profits is retained for
investment rather than being paid out to shareholders. If that argument
really takes hold, the Stock Market had better look to the consequences.
There is however a further aspect of the debate which is causing the City
anxiety. The more that companies cut dividends, the more the average company
pension fund will find itself running short of income. Companies which
enjoyed pension holidays in the 1980s may accordingly find their profits
affected by the necessity to top up their funds. The more that costs, the
less there is to invest in plant and machinery.
There is a further reason the government should not feel overly sanguine
about CBI members rushing to save the economy by investing. It is one thing
for the organisation's leaders to be called in to talk to the prime minister
or the chancellor, as has happened during the past weeks. The rank and file,
some of whom will doubtless return from Harrogate only to lay off more
workers, are not included in the general euphoria.
In yesterday's debate on the UK economy, two calls most vociferously
applauded were that the Bank of England should be granted independence and
that the Treasury should be sacked en masse.
It may well be a step forward that the government is taking the CBI
seriously. A more important step would be for the CBI's members to return
the compliment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
