<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Maastricht legislation faces
obstacle course - The bill's timetable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF ANY observer believed last week's government victory over Tory
Euro-sceptics marked the begining of the end of the Maastricht treaty's
ratification in the UK, the subsequent confusion has provided a sobering
lesson in the realities of Westminster procedures - and Conservative party
internal dynamics.
For government business managers trying to steer the bill through parliament
the way ahead resembles an obstacle course surrounded in fog. Nobody is
quite sure where the next hurdle lies or when the race will finish.
The outline timetable goes something like this:
Before Christmas the bill will return to the Commons for that start of its
'committee stage'. Two or three days will be set aside.
(The formal 'first reading' and two days of debate to give the bill a
'second reading,' and approve the broad principles of the legislation, took
place before the Danish referendum in June).
Euro-sceptics are certain to raise hundreds of points of order, each of
which has to be answered by Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Commons speaker. This
may take several days.
Work will then begin on the hundreds of amendments tabled by Maastricht's
opponents and the Labour and Liberal Democrat parties. Even though not all
of these will be chosen for debate, and many of those that are will be
grouped, that will still leave a substantial number of separate discussions,
each of which could last a few hours. In practice little headway will be
made with the substance of the bill before MPs break for Christmas.
Time will be allocated throughout the first half of next year for the
Committee stage to continue, with other legislation considered concurrently.
There is no hint yet that the government plans to bring in a 'guillotine'
motion which would timetable debate. The official line is that the
Maastricht treaty includes important constitutional change deserving serious
consideration.
But the unspoken sub-text is that Euro-sceptics were told last week that the
'third reading' - which follows the committee stage line-by-line
consideration of the whole bill - will not come before the second Danish
referendum.
This, the government argues, will not be until May. While some cabinet
ministers believe the referendum and the third reading are not
interdependent, Downing Street is sticking to the line that May is the most
likely time for the Danish poll - and the third reading.
What happens if the detailed committee stage debate collapses well before
then - so the third reading could take place in April - is not clear. Also
unclear is what happens should the referendum in Denmark be delayed beyond
May.
If the bill is to complete its passage before the end of the current session
 -as it must do unless the process has to start all over again  - it must go
to the House of Lords before the summer recess.
Peers' consideration of the bill cannot start until after the Commons' third
reading. The process in the Lords is a similar mix of debate in principle
and discussion of detail, finishing with a third reading debate.
Although by convention peers do not throw out a bill that is a manifesto
commitment, with many of Maastricht's most vociferous opponents in the upper
house - including Baroness Thatcher - its passage there will not necessarily
be smooth.
If the Lords has amended the bill at all, it must return to the Commons, as
the final form of the legislation has to be agreed by both MPs and peers.
If MPs refuse to accept changes made in the Lords, the bill could 'ping
pong' back and forth between the two chambers until agreement is reached -
although the Commons always has the final say. This could mean a last-minute
rush to get the bill though before the end of the session. Usually the date
for the state opening of the next session is fixed well in advance for
sometime in November. The Queen cannot be delayed.
In the final - and purely technical - stage, the Queen signifies her
agreement, and this Royal Assent turns the bill into an Act, completing the
parliamentary process.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-8702</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKJB2ACBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921110
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Obscure diners with a mind to spoil
the party - The new-found influence of the 92 Group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIME MINISTER John Major might be forgiven for wanting a quiet supper on
Thursday - the day his chancellor presents what looks set to be a
controversial Autumn Statement.
His diary will tell him he is unlikely to be granted such a wish, since he
is due to dine with the 92 Group of Thatcherite rightwingers.
This 100-strong group of Tory backbenchers contains many of the 'enemy
within': those MPs who have been making the government's life a misery in
recent weeks by exploiting its slender Commons majority to push for
climbdowns on key aspects of economic and European policy.
Over the weekend, it turned its attention to forcing a more favourable
balance in the ranks of the chief policy-makers themselves. This culminated
on Sunday with a public demand by Mr John Carlisle, MP for Luton North and a
92 Group member, for the prime minister to take 'an early opportunity to
redress that balance and have a cabinet more representative of popular and
party opinion.'
In terms of raw power, the 92 - under the guileful chairmanship of Sir
George Gardiner, the veteran MP for true-blue Reigate - has never been more
of a force to be reckoned with. The government's anaemic majority and the
large proportion of the new Tory intake who have swiftly become
card-carrying members have seen to that.
When Sir George said publicly that he and four colleagues were preparing to
support the government in last week's critical Maastricht divisions, it was
front-page news. Its members form a powerful bloc on the executive of the
1922 committee, which acts as mouthpiece-in-chief of Tory backbench opinion.
But in some ways, the increasingly public profile that the 92 has adopted
since April's general election is an ironic indication of waning influence.
During the Thatcher years, the group was able to concentrate instead on
working behind the scenes to secure the election of sympathetic candidates
to the chairs of the most important Tory backbench committees, emerging
occasionally to take issue with those whose conduct it considered beyond the
pale.
A sign of the obscurity in which it has traditionally operated lies in the
number of seasoned Westminster observers who wrongly believe that the 92
owes its name to the year of its foundation. In fact, this derives from the
address - 92 Cheyne Walk in fashionable Chelsea - where it was established
several years ago.
Now, as Mr Carlisle's remarks imply, the corridors of real power are
insufficiently lined with 92 group sympathisers however full of them the
back benches may be.
The less than stellar qualities of some of those being proposed as
replacements for 'targeted' ministers like Mr William Waldegrave, public
services minister, and Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, suggest that
this 'imbalance' may not quickly be corrected. Meanwhile, the views of those
deemed most likely to succeed Mr Major should he decide to throw in the
towel are if anything even less in tune with those on the right.
And there, in effect, is the rub: the nature of the 92 group's power is
purely destructive. If it is exercised to topple the present administration,
the group could be lumbered with a still more unsympathetic government.
If Mr Major is groping for an encouraging thought over the sherry on
Thursday, this may well be it.
</TEXT>
