<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour spells out plan for 'New
Deal'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR called on the government yesterday to abandon its hostility to an
industrial policy, set aside its planned spending cuts and use the public
sector as 'an engine of growth' to save the country from a slump.
Its plan for a 'British New Deal' also proposed to finance the package costs
by retaining stamp duty on share trans - actions, due to fall in April, and
by raising revenue through a one-off windfall levy on the turnover of the
privatised utility companies. The measures could be worth about Pounds 1.8bn
to the exchequer.
Labour's recovery programme came before a similar exercise today by the
Liberal Democrats as both parties try to pre-empt Thursday's Autumn
Statement by issuing alternative public-expenditure prescriptions.
Both parties will use their proposals as benchmarks against which to measure
those of Mr Norman Lamont. If the chancellor adopts some of their plans, he
will be accused of poaching and, where he does not, he will stand charged of
failing to do enough.
The Labour package fleshes out earlier demands for a comprehensive programme
of employment and training measures, valued at about Pounds 350m, capital
spending on environmental improvements and the phased release of local
authorities' capital receipts to boost house-building.
Announcing the package, shadow chancellor Mr Gordon Brown also called for a
cut in interest rates, investment incentives for industry, grants for medium
and smaller businesses, an export drive and talks with industrialists on
boosting output and sales.
Questioned on whether Labour would raise tax, he dismissed any such move as
likely to depress demand and rejected increased national insurance
contributions, now rumoured to be part of Mr Lamont's proposals.
He also appeared to have put on ice Labour's controversial 'shadow budget',
unveiled before the April election, which included the lifting of the
ceiling on NICs.
Mr Brown also said there should be changes to public accounting procedures,
supervised by a new council of independent economic advisers and
co-ordinated Community-wide efforts to stimulate growth.
Warning against 'one-off cosmetic initiatives' and short-term packages, he
said: 'The key is the immediate recovery programme accompanied by a long
term strategy for sustainable growth.'
In advance of unveiling the Liberal Democrats' recovery proposals today, Mr
Malcolm Bruce, the party's trade and industry spokesman, yesterday gave
examples of construction projects which could be launched quickly and would
create at least 450,000 jobs.
The measures, which they estimate would cost more than Pounds 4bn of public
money, include track renewal for British Rail; support for light railway
systems in areas such as the west Midlands and Leeds; and improvements to
the trunk road system.
The Liberal Democrats are keen that the row between the two main opposition
parties over last week's vote on Europe should not prevent them from working
together against the government's public spending plans.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, has written privately to Mr John Smith,
urging co-operation over the Autumn Statement.
</TEXT>
