<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / Repaying debt is consumer priority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS, unconvinced by lower interest rates, continued to make the
repayment of debt a priority last month.
Official figures out yesterday showed that consumers paid back Pounds 60m
more than they borrowed in September following a net repayment of Pounds 36m
in August.
Almost all of last month's fall in consumer credit was accounted for by a
big reduction in credit card debts. Lending by banks on credit cards that
are part of the Visa or Mastercard system fell by Pounds 58m, compared with
a fall of only Pounds 3m in August. Net lending by finance houses rose by
Pounds 6m, while loans by building societies fell by Pounds 8m.
The figures from the Central Statistical Office also showed that new credit
advanced to consumers rose to Pounds 4.4bn in September compared with Pounds
3.8bn in August. Economists said that last month's higher figure probably
reflected a big rise in loans on household goods, following a rush to buy
houses in August, before the stamp duty concession was removed.
Mr Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brother said: 'Although
consumer credit remains weak, it has not shown a fresh collapse over the
summer.'
A broader measure of credit growth which includes bank loans on personal
accounts and lending by non-bank credit cards shows an acceleration in net
consumer credit growth in the latest quarter, compared with the second
quarter.
In the three months to the end of September, consumer lending according to
this measure expanded by Pounds 332m compared with the second quarter's
exceptionally low figure of Pounds 155m.
Although the narrow measure of consumer borrowing represents only about 15
per cent of total private sector debt - it does not include mortgages - it
is a useful snapshot on consumer behaviour.
The latest figures, for example, show that in the third quarter, consumer
credit fell by Pounds 18m, reflecting caution about the economic situation
and the high cost of borrowing. The figure compares with growth of Pounds
202m in the third quarter last year, and growth of Pounds 786m in the third
quarter of 1990.
</TEXT>
