FT  10 NOV 92 / British Coal rounds on critics over lost sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL yesterday rejected criticism that it had lost an opportunity to
sell large quantities of coal to ScottishPower when it responded to the
electricity generation and supply company's request for coal supply
quotations.
ScottishPower had asked coal producers to quote for the supply of 250,000
tonnes and indicated that it would consider buying further quantities if the
price was right.
Last week it agreed to buy 250,000 tonnes from British Coal and awarded
contracts for 100,000 tonnes from private Scottish opencast mines, plus
840,000 tonnes from suppliers in Australia, Poland, the former Soviet Union
and the US.
When ScottishPower's orders were announced, British Coal said that if it had
known the electricity company was interested in buying more than 250,000
tonnes it would have tendered accordingly.
ScottishPower said the tender document stated that it was prepared to buy
more than the basic tonnage and that it used the same wording as previous
tenders. In a 1991 tender, British Coal's offer of more than ScottishPower
had requested was accepted.
Yesterday Mr Malcolm Edwards, who resigned as British Coal's marketing
director earlier this year after a disagreement with Mr Neil Clarke,
chairman of the company, said: 'This is a very important bit of business
which is unlikely to recur.'
British Coal was unable to confirm yesterday that it had several hundred
thousand tonnes of opencast coal stockpiled on the surface in Scotland which
could have been sold to ScottishPower. It will anyway supply ScottishPower
with 2.5m tonnes of coal this year under contracts running to 1995.
