FT  10 NOV 92 / FT Satellite Monitor: Fall in sales of TV dishes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALES of satellite dishes were significantly down last month compared with
October last year and there is little sign that the Christmas selling period
has taken off.
The FT satellite monitor survey for last month found that 71,000 dishes had
been installed compared with 61,000 in September. In October last year more
than 100,000 dishes were sold or rented followed by a similar number in
November.
There has been a shortage of dishes from both Amstrad and Pace over the last
few weeks but this has now been eased. A Pounds 5m winter advertising
campaign has been launched.
November's sales figure should show whether the slowdown has been caused by
dish shortages or by a dampening of demand.
Over the past three years satellite television has grown at an average rate
of 900,000 homes a year and the new satellite television channels are now
available in 3.08m homes.
There has been a modest increase in demand, according to the monitor, which
is carried out for the Financial Times by Continental Research. Those saying
they will definitely or probably install satellite television rose from
1.58m in September to 1.96m last month.
Over the three months from July television viewing figures for satellite
homes show satellite television increasing its share of the audience from 29
per cent to 31 per cent.
Pearson, the publishers of the Financial Times, has a significant stake in
British Sky Broadcasting, the largest satellite TV operator.
