FT  10 NOV 92 / Cheaper electricity at risk, power chief warns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHIEF executive of National Power, the UK's largest electricity
generator, warned yesterday that protection of vested interests in the
energy industry may jeopardise the prospect of cheaper electricity.
Mr John Baker said that 'though it is inevitably going to be a slow process,
I have no doubt that electricity prices in the UK will continue to fall in
real terms as competition bites and cost savings continue to be passed to
the end user.'
He added, however, that this scenario assumed no outside intervention to
protect vested interests and to reduce the impact of market forces.
Mr Baker's warning was made at a Financial Times conference in London on
World Electricity, as he prepared to give evidence in the House of Commons
today to the select committee inquiring into the future of coal.
Mr Baker said the reorganisation of the UK electricity industry had shown
there was no 'immutable law which says electricity prices can only go up,
not down.' Competition was already providing significant impetus towards
lower prices when in Europe as a whole real prices tended to remain
stubbornly high.
'One reason is that a number of European countries have preferred a policy
of subsidising uneconomic domestic energy sources to buying more
competitively prices fuel in open world markets,' he said.
Mr James Hann, chairman of Scottish Nuclear, speaking at the same
conference, called on the government to take a longer term approach to
energy planning and to move more rapidly towards a coherent energy policy
for the UK.
Mr Hann said that market forces may not be sufficient alone to guarantee
security of supply at 'competitive prices and without damaging the
environment beyond repair.'
</TEXT>
