<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / Reporting rules on pensions changed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES will be required to show the impact of post-retirement benefits
such as medical costs more quickly and in more detail in their accounts,
under a tough new ruling introduced yesterday by the Urgent Issues Task
Force of the Accounting Standards Board (ASB).
Abstract 6 from the task force broadens the principles specified in SSAP 24,
the accounting standard for pension costs, to include other forms of
post-retirement benefits.
The ruling will principally affect UK companies with US subsidiaries, where
private medical costs and other benefits incurred by former employees run
into many millions of pounds.
It specifies that a company must show an annual charge through the profit
and loss account based on actuarial assumptions of the present value of any
future post-retirement benefits to be paid.
It will also have to show provisional liabilities in the balance sheet to
reflect these future costs, with a corresponding reduction in shareholders'
funds.
At present, most post-retirement benefits other than pensions are not
specifically funded by the company in advance. They are simply paid for and
treated in the accounts on a cash basis by being shown only in the year in
which they are paid out.
The new ruling instead follows the accruals principal by which accounts are
generally prepared. It echoes the line taken by FAS 106, a similar standard
on post-retirement benefits introduced recently by the Financial Accounting
Standards Board in the US.
The new consensus also requires additional disclosures in the accounts to
show any important assumptions for the measurement of post-retirement
benefits.
It becomes mandatory for companies' financial year-ends after December 23
1994, with transitional requirements after December 23 this year.
Separately, Fred 2, a draft financial reporting exposure draft which amends
SSAP 15, the existing accounting standard on deferred tax, proposes that
annual contributions on pensions and other post-retirement benefits can be
paid net of tax.
Fred 2. Amendment to SSAP 15: accounting for deferred tax. Accountancy
Books, PO Box 620, Central Milton Keynes MK9 WJX. Pounds 1.50
</TEXT>
