<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 92 / What future for coal?: Australia sees market chance in pit
closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE upheaval in the British coal industry comes as little surprise to
Australia which, as the world's leading coal exporter, has long seen the
rationalisation of much of Europe's coal production as inevitable.
Australia's industry could scarcely contrast more strongly with its British
counterpart. Australian producers see themselves as leading the world coal
industry with modern and expanding operations based on private ownership. Mr
Rod Charlton, manager, coal marketing services for Australia's MIM Holdings,
says his industry is targeting the UK for growth in sales of steaming coal -
largely used for power generation.
'Many Australian steaming coal brands have been successfully tested in the
UK and pit closures give us the chance to pick up business,' he says.
'We're not looking to the closures as a huge boost to our sales, but they
will reduce the excess thermal coal supply on world markets. In combination
with new power station building programmes in the Asia-Pacific region and
the probable closure of some German mines, the outlook over the next five
years is for steady improvement in the supply demand balance.'
Such an improvement would be welcome for the Australian industry which is
grappling with spot prices for thermal coal - used for steam raising - which
are about 25 per cent below contract rates. These spot prices are largely
unprofitable to Australian producers, even in Asia where they have a strong
freight advantage.
If UK electricity authorities were to seek replacement tonnage for British
Coal supplies through spot tenders, Australian producers would be unlikely
to feature as significant bidders. A freight disadvantage of about USDollars
6 a tonne against South African and US competitors would render UK spot
business unprofitable for almost all Australian suppliers.
The Australian industry's awareness of likely trends in the UK coal industry
was evident in a survey of world coal markets commissioned in May, 1991,
from Sydney-based consultants, Barlow Jonker.
The survey forecast continuing mine closures in Britain, leading to an
increased reliance on imported coal, though this was likely to be offset by
increased use of gas for power generation.
Like its UK counterpart, the Australian coal industry has not avoided
closures in recent years. The difference has been that most Australian
closures have been related to expansion of more efficient facilities which
have more than offset production cuts.
The result has been continuing overall growth in Australian coal production,
while productivity has more than doubled in the past decade to stand at
6,150 tonnes of saleable output per employee per year in 1991-92.
Much of this improvement reflects capital spending on modern plant and the
Barlow Jonker survey indicated the industry would need to spend a further
Dollars A3bn (Pounds 1.36bn) by 1995 to keep pace with expected Asian demand
growth.
But these expenditure plans come against a background of falling prices for
export coal. Latest earnings statistics from the Australian Coal Association
showed that almost half the coal companies in New South Wales incurred
losses in the latest period. Queensland, the other main coal exporting
state, does not release figures, but the ratio there is likely to have been
worse.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
